The paper deals with human action recognition using dynamic probabilistic networks (DPN) and focuses on the interrelation between various regions of interest (ROI) on the human body. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the use of DPNs for classification indicates that the paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The focus on human behavior and recognition accuracy performance suggests that the paper may also belong to the human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Finally, the use of time series data and the testing of classification accuracy in different lighting conditions suggests that the paper may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
